snippet.title: Best tech cars
snippet.description: The following cars represent the most technically advanced available.

snippet.title: 2015 Ford F-150
snippet.description: Ford's F-150 has been the best-selling truck in the US for the past 37 years in a row. This year it gets a radical overhaul, moving to aluminum to save weight and getting a raft of new tech inside and out, making sure this workhorse continues to carry the Blue Oval forward.

snippet.title: 2014 Ford Escape SE
snippet.description: The 2014 Ford Escape SE is a fantastic example of "less is more," making acceptable power with a tiny engine and offering exceptional tech in even its base configuration.

snippet.title: 2013 Ford Fusion Hybrid
snippet.description: The 2013 Ford Fusion Hybrid looks good and can be had with very advanced driver assistance features, but buyers should expect fuel economy averaging around 40 mpg instead of the 47 mpg EPA test number.

snippet.title: 2014 Ford Fiesta ST
snippet.description: Inexpensive yet high-performing, the 2014 Ford Fiesta ST rewards people who enjoy driving, while cabin electronics support all those mundane tasks that need doing when not on a twisty back road.

snippet.title: 2015 Ford Focus
snippet.description: Ford's chosen to unveil it's new compact at Mobile World Congress, a week ahead of the big auto show in Geneva. It packs better tech inside, new driver aids, and a subtly revised exterior.

snippet.title: 2013 Ford C-Max Hybrid
snippet.description: Offering all the fuel economy and practical interior space of a Toyota Prius, the 2013 Ford C-Max Hybrid adds significant power and a more engaged driving experience.

snippet.title: 2015 Ford Mustang
snippet.description: For the 50th anniversary of the iconic Mustang, Ford isn't exactly reinventing the wheel, but the company's latest pony car looks to be the best yet.

snippet.title: 2014 Ford Fiesta
snippet.description: With its 1.6-liter engine, the 2014 Ford Fiesta makes for a mild-mannered urban runabout, but Sync and MyFord Touch add some compelling tech features.

snippet.title: Samsung to buy OLED maker Novaled for $347 million
snippet.description: The deal would help Samsung with the increasing demand for the OLED screens used in smartphones and televisions.
